review_data.review: We stayed at a hotel nearby and the staff there recommended this restaurant. It was amazing!  You get an Argentine feel as soon as you enter... delicious food smells in the air, lots of wood decor, great ambiance.  Our Portuguese speaking server did not speak English however the menus had an English translation and with some pointing and hand waving we managed to order.  To say that the food was great would be a big understatement. Our steaks were the best that we had ever eaten! We are still talking about them and wondering if we'll ever have the chance to eat any that taste that good again. They were grilled and seasoned to perfection... not to mention VERY generous portions. The side dishes were plentiful and delicious as well.  And at the end of the meal, we were surprised by the bill... at how small it was! There were four of us dining and we had four steaks, four side dishes, a bottle of wine, a large bottle of beer and several bottles of water - our bill worked out to about $20 US each! Unbelievable for such a delicious and plentiful meal.  Needless to say we highly recommend this restaurant for an authentic Argentine experience and the best steaks you'll ever eat. If we return to Buenos Aires again, we will definitely dine here again!

Service of food was fast although when the restaurant filled up there was a delay for the bill. This is because there are problems finding staff due to Covid, Brexit and furlough and no doubt will be addressed. We will certainly return although I don't know whether they dance on tables in the evening. The bill for 2 was around £50 including service.

We were guests of a local company when we visited this restaurant earlier this week. We ate the most amazing food and we’re served by delightful, professional and courteous staff. Lovely Riad restaraunt, difficult to find but find it we did. Lovely setting with attentive professional staff. The food was wonderful, tasty and very well presented. This place is terrific! It's Greek cuisine but it's terrific for fish. We had the Greek spreads as appetizers along with the best grilled octopus we have ever had. We’ve searched everywhere to find the best Thai food on Phuket. There are some very good ones but best to our opinion is Dee Plee. The staff could be a bit more attentive and look a bit better to their guests but … the kitchen make this more as good again. Highly recommended for quality Thai food seekers.

Found this restaurant on TripAdvisor. They serve good food to a very reasonable price. Nice clean restaurant to high western standards. Very friendly service. The only drawback is that its difficult to find for the average tourist.

review_data.review_title: Excellent, Creative Food, Attentive Service but Unnecessary Rush
review_data.review: We went for Indian Feast Menu and loved it. The modern twist to some of the traditional Indian dishes was interesting and intriguing. It was a treat indeed. However there is once serious flaw: uncalled for, super-sonic serving speed. As one can see from my reviews, I have been to a number of top-notched restaurants, the world over, quite often opting degustation menu to experience their gastronomical skills, to the fullest. Tasting or Degustation menu is meant to make guests enjoy each and every bite of the dishes served, at a philosophical pace, and relaxed mood. Many places normally serve palate cleanser before each new dish arrives. They work to remove any aftertastes lingering in the mouth so that guests can enjoy each dish without continuing to taste the last. Surprisingly, V Zátiší serves some of its dishes in pairs which results sometimes in different [and wrong] combination than what is intended or appropriate and sometimes, one of the dishes getting cold, losing its lustre. V Zatisi opts to bulldoze it through. Exaggerating a little bit, of course. I am unable to see any culinary justification or business rationale for this unnecessary haste. I would dare to state that it is a cardinal sin to spoil a superb concept in this way.

review_data.review_title: Great place, great food, a MUST GO in Paris!
review_data.review: Let me start with the dessert. Honestly, the Maitre can be relaxed now and lay back. I have to admit: one chocolate dessert on the menu and I will go for it. This one was exceptional. Great Praline mousse, nice chocolate sphere, nice crumble combination. It was death of chocolate, a very nice one. So let me begin with the starter. The champignons de bois had an excellent taste, an amazing texture. The salad topping was not mine, but all in a bite very good. The main course was an Argentine Entrecote, cooked to perfection. All these dishes are presented in a good manner at a nice location. The ambiance is great, following the theme of this restaurant. The host and the staff in general: keen, nice, helpful and attentive. Nothing to complain about and to be honest: we ate worse at Michelin Star restaurants. The location of the restaurant cannot be found without TripAdvisor. Hence, no mass tourism and no tourists who want to eat cheap and fast. We had a great evening and an absolutely fantastic dinner. This restaurant needs to be visited for sure!

Very first restaurant once we arrived in Marrakech and it was a good start. Despite of the fact that we had chosen French Cuisine we did not regret this. All dishes were cooked to perfection and the choice of fresh herbs and spices was excellent. We had lobster for starter to be continued with a great steak in a kind of Bernaise gravy. Was delicious. The hosts are very friendly and even the Maitre appeared at the table to ask for feedback. Well done. I finished that meal with a Cafe Gourmet which was a good choice. The only cons was that inside of restaurants in Morocco it is still allowed to smoke, a pitty especially in restaurants like this where you want to discover all tastes. Finally, we strongly recommend this place for sure and advice you to have a reservation in advance.

Let me put it this way: a nice dinner that evening including cat entertainment. Palette is the star of this restaurant. Straying around the tables you get a visit from here once food is ready. What a funny moment. On our arrival she started her nap at the table next to me. In the moment the starters arrived she immediately woke up and started to „check“ what is going on there. We loved it. Let me get to the starters. The homemade foie gras I choose was delicious but slightly overpriced. 21 Euros for one single slice is too much. Even at Michelin rated restaurants the portion would be better. The main course was great, nothing to complain about. Good usage of spices and herbs, was a nice dish and good eventing. We can recommend this place.
What a great surprise! French restaurant operated by French people. Great service and wonderful food!!!

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Shockingly impersonal hosts. Decent food, nothing really outstanding! Mediocre Wines.
review_data.review: We had an OK night at casa SaltShaker, but in the end it was a disappointmet, because we  expected MUCH more.  First of all, the food was ok - there's nothing to complain about. However, it wasn't anyting really special. This is definitely NOT world class, in a city famous for its abundance of world class restaurants. Of course, this insight was a disappointment!  The best way to describe what I mean is:  If I was invited to a hobby cook's house and he cooked such a meal, it would be great. If however somebody pretending to be a knowledgable chef invited me to his and cooked this menu for me, I would clearly think that he was not trying nearly as hard as he could, but was saving efforts...  The Casa Saltshaker guys are definitely to be attributed to the hobby cook area...the problem is that TA rates them in the other category (and they think that they belong there...)  The HUGE DISAPPOINTMENT was however was the complete abscence of any personal interaction on behalf of the "hosts". When you "invite" somebody into your home and you do not wish to exchange even a word with your "guests", this is really a bummer. I had the feeling that they were desperate to put us through the process as quickly as possible, collect our money and send us home.  I certainly didn't feel welcome there.  Exemplatory for the attitude towards their guest was this episode:  Coming in I was thirsty and aksed for a glass of water. They rejected it by saying that they would start serving dinner in 10min. REALLY!? Is THAT hospitality?! No one had ever before denied me a glass of water :-)  Making up for the desaster that our hosts were was a quite nice mix of guests with whom we've had a fun evening anyway, despite the hosts (unfortunately not because of them :-)  Last but not least, the wine "pairing" we had with the meal was mediocre. We have had wine pairings in good places in Buenos Aires, so we know what can be expected in this price range. The guys either don't have a clue about wine or they simply don't care (I suppose it's the latter, because it fits the overall picture).

review_data.review_title: Back for the Wines in a Beautiful Venue
review_data.review: Back for the Wines in a Beautiful Venue  We first discovered The Park Room at the JW Marriott Grosvenor House Park Lane Mayfair/London, when waiting for an event, with the Arizona Cardinals NFL Football team. They were in London for a game, and were using the JW Marriott as their base of operations. I then have returned several more times, and been impressed each time. In December, we were back to London, and on a totally leisure trip. We were staying just down Park Lane from the JW Marriott, and my wife asked if we could go to The Park Room for drinks. Well, that was a no-brainer - wines with my wife, with no meetings looming over her head, in a lovely space, just blocks from us. Off we went.  Now, there are three areas of The Park Room, and two are mostly attached, plus a lounge area, just around the corner, with a grand piano, which is more open to the reception area of the lobby. We were seated in the lounge area, near the piano, and I had the wine list in hand quickly. On this afternoon, the pianist was playing, and I think that this is only the second time, when he has been there - quite, quite good! Though the main dining room is gorgeous, one of the things that I like about the lounge area is that it has more of an open view of the attractive lobby - though no views out onto Park Lane, as that main dining area has.  We did the Henri de Villamont Clos Du Cromin Meursault ‘13, the Guillaume Vrignaud Fourchaume Chablis 1er Cru ‘15, and the Spelt “La Valentina” Montepulciano D’Abruzzo Riserva DOC ‘14. The wine service was great, but while the stemware was attractive (those are Park Room “signature glasses”), I was not that big a fan of the open bowl design - lovely to look at, but not my favorite for wines.  It’s now a tossup, whether I like the main dining room, or this little lounge area the better, but that might depend on whether the pianist is playing. We will be returning, as we have since making this discovery, a few years back.  Though this September visit was our first stay at the JW Marriott Grosvenor House Park Lane Mayfair/London, I had visited The Park Room twice before, once solo, and once with a friend, but this was the very first visit for my wife.  We had arrived from the States a bit too early to check into our room, in the hotel - but this was no surprise, as we had to take a flight out of LAX, rather than SFO, so knew we would be at least an hour - or two - early. That was not to be helped. We did the formalities, and told the reservations agent that we would just find some Champagne in the Park Room.  On this early Spring afternoon, it was as lovely, as I remembered it to be, with sunlight streaming through the windows, overlooking Park Lane, and Hyde Park. This is an elegant room, there is no denying, but it is also a very comfortable room, at least it was for us.  We were seated by the welcoming hostess, at a nice little 2-top, in the main dining area. While not against the windows, we still had a lovely view. From my previous experience, I believe that the dining area, at those windows, is most often used for Afternoon Tea, as it has much more of a salon feel, and look to it. We were in the main dining area, just behind that salon.  We had the wine list in hand, and settled in to relax, enjoy ourselves, and await our room assignment - knowing that we probably had at least an hour, or more.  We started with Perrier-Jouët Blanc de Blanc, and a glass of the Perrier-Jouët Blason Rosé. Both were served in lovely flutes.  We sipped, and relaxed, as we had been flying for quite some time, and when the Champagne was gone, moved on to Soellner Grüner Veltliner Fumburg ‘16 (a new wine to me), and the Henri de Villamont Meursault ‘15 (also a new producer - we were having fun now).  About half of the way through the still whites, our reservations agent arrived, and offered to show us to our suite, as soon as we had finished the wine. She made certain to give our server the room number, for the charges, which was a nice touch, as we did not need to bother with a credit card.  The afternoon had almost slipped by, and the wait was of no issue. We were in a lovely room, watching Hyde Park across the way, with excellent, and very friendly and attentive service, plus getting to explore some new wines. What a great way to start a holiday. I am so glad that my wife finally got to experience The Park Room, and now it was time to unpack, shower, and head back down to the lobby for dinner - with even more wine!

They also brought another dish for my husband's birthday. If you're afraid of spicy Korean flavors, nothing here was too spicy (or spicy at all), but the Korean flavors were evident in all the dishes. It was really the perfect combination of Korean and French. I highly recommend it!

review_data.review_title: Fabulous food at a cozy place
review_data.review: We went there twice in our 4 day stay at Siem Reap as we liked it so much. Kids loved the relaxed seating arrangement and it was so convenient to keep them occupied with the books available for reading at the restaurant. Food was delicious for incredible little price and the portion sizes were adequate. Would highly recommend this place for anyone visiting Siem Reap.

Excellent food. We had the Sunday lunch with Prosecco. Self service antipasti which was so fresh and a great variety. So good we went up twice. The risotto was divine for the second course; so hot and fresh. My husband had Guinea fowl and I had lamb, again both so tasty. The Guinea fowl was on a crostini, so tasty and perfectly cooked. My lamb was served with ratatouille. We both finished off with the ice cream and iced espresso. They piped in chocolate, Happy Birthday for my husband, a nice touch. Our waiter George was very attentive and did a really good job. Our glasses were frequently topped up with Prosecco and glasses of water. Lovely fresh, rustic restaurant with a lovely ambiance. Live musician was also really good. Beautiful hotel with a bar for pre dinner drinks. Literally a couple of minutes walk from Hyde Park Corner tune station. Families dining there but well behaved children.

simply an amazing restaurant. Here is another example of a social profit agency that works the restaurant business and puts $$$ back into the community. You just have to go there. The food, music, decor, ambience and customer service is Outstanding.

This is another amazing social profit enterprise. They take in disadvantaged youth. They train, educate, coach and mentor young adults to be self-sustaining and employed in today’s world. They also run a 1st class restaurant with excellent food, ambience and incredible customer service. Thank You for what you do.

They take in disadvantaged youth - train them in life skills, work skills, hospitality management - being servers, cooks , chefs , managers etc. Then trainees are sent out to other hotels for internships and then after graduation they all find jobs in the local Siem Reap hospitality industry. A remarkable process. Train your staff well and they will look after your customers.

This restaurant is a dream and a Haven for dis-advantaged youth. Paul and his wife ( owners) started this project in order to provide youth with an opportunity to acquire life, work and employment skills. Youth go through an internship process for a number of months. When they graduate they are hired at local high-end restaurants as they have excellent hospitality skills, knowledge abilities. So, when in Siem Reap you will have to eat , so I ask that you dine at this restaurant support their cause.

I found this restaurant on TA / the reviews are very good and decided to try one of it’s Khmer stir fry dishes the menu is varied and has Khmer, Thai and some western food choices as well. The chicken stir fry was excellent - lots of fresh veggies and lots of really nice breast of chicken. The sauce was great, thanks - will be back again .
Simply amazing menu choices - super fresh, healthy, wholesome, delicious and great customer service. Whoo Hoo I highly recommend this restaurant

we always stop in and have dinner or lunch @ Tevy’s Place. Tevy and her staff are so welcoming. Excellent service and menu choices at a very reasonable price. She brings in and trains young women in all aspects of running a restaurant. Thanks for being a successful entrepreneur and for training, coaching and mentoring young adults.

I love this restaurant. The food was s 12/10 , interesting ambience, great staff and excellent customer service . If you sit a front you can watch them cook your meal. All female staff. review_data.review_title: Surprise visit last minute dot com
review_data.review: Last minute find! Checked reviews and wasn’t disappointed a gem in Bruce Grove, intimate friendly and very helpful staff. Food menu enough for most tastes😉

I have to admit based on the location, website and price point we were expecting a "wow." It looks like the restaurant is under Michelin consideration and they need to step it up. Lovely decor and presentation, but the food somehow just doesn't live up to expectations. We have traveled to India and are frequent diners at the small places in Edison, NJ (little India) -- places where you get wow (but definitely NOT atmosphere cheap). Utsav is very convenient to theaters, and has a prix fixe menu. We did a combo of small plates, entrees and dessert. The small plates were both excellent -- traditional samosas and a quinoa potato patty. The mains less so. The menu has a combination of traditional and different, and my husband's Baingan Bharta (eggplant) was enjoyable. I had the Shrimp Goa, which was supposed to come in a coconut sauce. It was basically Shrimp Tikka Masala, and it was overcooked. I mean to the point of tough. I've had that issue in Indian places before, but that is a rookie mistake to be sure. Short on time I did not send it back, but also did not love it. The dessert was again quite good, a traditional kheer but with coconut sorbet in the middle. The entire meal cost $150 for 3 people (tax and tip included -- no alcohol). In Edison it's usually about $65 and we have tons left over. I highly doubt we will be back.

I cannot speak more highly of this restaurant — from its mission, to the service to the food — everything was top notch. Their mission is to train disadvantaged youth to work in the hospitality industry. They have a 16 month training program and support these youth throughout. Our servers were a mix of newer and experienced people. Everyone truly cared that you enjoy what you have, and the atmosphere. We had some outstanding food, including a tofu sate (the peanut sauce was to die for), the pumpkin soup (creamy and rich), the fish with mango salad and bananas in coconut milk (yum!). We ate in the courtyard which was quite charming. Reasonable prices. 5 stars!!

Les Apotres was just around the corner from our hotel apartment and had sensational reviews. It becomes a bit cramped with so many people and tables in such a small place (reminded me in way of dining at the Golden Temple in Amritsar). The ordering process is a bit different too - you take a menu sheet and tick what you want - no traditional waiters. The owners clearly know a thing or two about hospitality as the good feeling you get here is all about the food and style. All the dishes we ate were simple, exquisite and original - great flavours.

Tiny place that I walked passed several times in this "industrial" street, otherwise the home of tyre sellers, watch sellers, carpet sellers and the like. There are only 24 seats, mostly on the mezzanine area. It appears basic but noticeably clean and tidy. The menu is a blend of Moroccan and international with everything from pizzas, pastas, burgers, salads, traditional Moroccan, crepes, soups. I enjoyed a really good home made courgette and vegetable soup followed by spaghetti bolognese and fruit salad and mint tea (served with complimentary Moroccan biscuits/pastries). As it got busier there was pressure on the speed of service - but I was in no hurry - but all through there was a pride and passion for what was being served and how it was presented. Very inexpensive, an extensive menu and caring service made this place instantly likeable. Good on ya Yassine!

The Bunker Restaurant is set in moody dark space. The welcoming smile from Emma was lovely on arrival as was the cocktail bar service from Claudio which was warm and jovial followed by waiting service from Emma, Penny and Adam with professionalism and a smile. Thanks also to the kitchen crew who made the delicious degustation dinner.

For some reason, Sandbox's kitchen puts out consistently well tasting dishes but clearly Takieng is struggling and not exactly in the inexpensive side.

Slight mix up with starters but quality of burgers made up for this so still 5 star review

My wife and I had been traveling SE Asia for a month and enjoyed everything from Street food to Michelin star quality.  We where unsure where to try a 'high end' meal in Hanoi, after being given several inconsistent recommendations by previous visitors or tour guides.  For us, Cloud Nine fitted the bill perfectly and we enjoyed our first visit so much that we chose to return again on our final night in Asia.  Located in the La Siesta Hàng be Hotel, just below the rooftop bar (both reviewed elsewhere) its central to the Old Quarter but has far reaching views in all directions across the city. The decor is undoubtedly chic, with a hint of French presented with a wonderful Asian style and finesse.  They served a mix of Vietnamese and western food, although we only ate from the Vietnamese menu.  They offer a tasting menu at £17 per head but each night we chose to dine a la carte and spent a little more (approx. £25 excluding drinks) but the food, quality, preparation and presentation was absolutely first class.  What sets this restaurant apart though is the quality of service. Anyone who has traveled in SE Asia will know that, if you pay a little more, the quality of service is consistently good. Here it was truly exceptional.  From the very first moment, restaurant supervisor/ maitre d', Amber, ensures that you're welcomed, relaxed and served to your satisfaction. Not that she should have any concerns, as the staff are all, without exception, attentive and polite.  On both occasions we ate here, our server was Huyen. An absolute delight to deal with, her English was seriously impressive, indeed we found her easier to understand than some of our more heavily accented tour guides! She really exceeded any reasonable expectations of service.  On our return visit we were both treated like long lost friends and we'll take memories such as that away with us.  For the record, over our two visits, we ate the special chef spring rolls, Hanoi deep fried spring rolls, Phu Bo, asparagus and crab meat soup, Tom Yum Kung soup, green mango seafood salad, beef on hot stones and Tiger prawns in coconut. We never made it to dessert! In addition, they serve a complimentary amuse bouche to start and a refreshing drink to close.  A truly wonderful experience and I would highly recommend.

review_data.review: Experiencing the tasting menu at this restaurant is my highest recommendation and top tip following a month long visit to SE Asia.  We are fortunate to have eaten some excellent meals on five continents but this restaurant served us one of top five meals of all time.  The restaurant is staffed throughout by females and, without wishing to sound sexist, I truly believe you can taste and experience their delicate and feminine touch throughout.  My wife and I were privileged to enjoy their seven course, regularly changing, tasting menu and were rewarded with some exceptional, exquisite tastes. Presentation and service were exemplary too.  Combined with a four glass classic wine pairing for me and a four cup tea tasting for my wife, the cost isn't cheap in Siem Reap terms but at $36 per person for food, $29 for four glass of paired wine or $15 for four deliciously flavoured teas, it's incredible value for money given the quality of food, presentation and service on offer.  In addition we were given complementary amuse bouche to start, had opportunity to thank one of the chefs direct and were given a leaving gift of their exquisitely presented, complementary macaroons.  An exceptional experience that I would repeat in a heartbeat, I cannot recommend this restaurant more highly.  Do not miss.

I would recommend trying this bar for some unique tastes.

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Tasty new Indian restaurant in town

I ordered the paneer tikka masala which was delicious and they were generous with the paneer which I appreciated. The mango lassi was also very tasty. Pricing is similar to other Indian restaurants in town but I would say Rasoi Ghar is one of the better Indian restaurants that I’ve tried in Siem Reap and I’ve tried a fair few.
The service, food and atmosphere here are all first class. Watching the sunset while sipping cocktails on the terrace is truly relaxing.
Our second time dining at this wonderful restaurant. A truly memorable experience from start to finish. Great food, amazing service - the staff are the best we have encountered during our travels.

review_data.review_title: THE best restaurant in Marrakech. As simple as that.
review_data.review: It's a convoluted route to get to Pepe Nero, but what a glorious experience when you arrive. We had a week in Marrakech, and this is far and away the best restaurant - infinitely better than the posh restaurants around the main squares and far, far better than the supposedly typical Moroccan eateries within the expensive hotels. It's Italian cooking, and Moroccan cooking - two menus; you take your choice, or mix and match from both. The chef trained in London and Italy, and brought his expertise here. The food is very good, the wine even better (feel free to ask if you can taste before you choose, and the extremely helpful waiters will oblige) and the setting sublime, with rose petals in the central fountain, handy loos off the huge courtyard, interesting little atmospheric side rooms and up-and-down, higgeldy-piggeldy steps and corridors everywhere. Housed within the Riyad al Moussika in Derb Charkaoui, it took us about 20 minutes to walk to the restaurant, down a series of winding alleyways and streets, following the black signs, from Jamaa el Fna. However, it only took us 5 minutes to get back at the end of the evening, as we were allowed to leave via the kitchens and a secret back route! The food is excellent. I began with salmon tartare, the only criticism being that some of the avocado pieces in the assemblage weren't totally ripe. My bride had a starter of warm aubergine - a bit like Turkish aubergine dishes. My main course was tortellini - home made in a rich, creamy parmesan sauce. My bride opted for risotto with shrimp. All dishes top-notch, and very filling. The service is terrific, with sparky, cheeky waiters who love a bit of banter. This is a restaurant to enjoy and experience. Pre-booking essential as it, understandably, sells out most evenings. We had an excellent bottle of Moroccan wine - a 2016 Medaillon cabernet for around £25. Total price for two, including water and service, was about £80 sterling equivalent. If this restaurant was in the UK or Europe, it would be 'bib gourmand' status in the Michelin ratings.

The restaurant is located on the hills of the hotel, overlooking the hotel grounds, the sea and the beach. The decoration of the hotel is perfect, in Lanna style (northern thailand style) and the Lanna inspiration can be traced back in the menu... !  The menu is traditional thai with a number of plates from northern thailand (which is a different style from the south of thailand). Everything we ordered came in a very nice presentation and all the tastes were just amazing!! We had the possibility to have different type of rice, which is always great since Thailand has so much to offer on this front. The staff was super friendly and smiling and they contribute very significantly to the overall experience you have at Dee Plee. To me, Dee Plee is part of those restaurants who are truly honoring Thai food by offering to the guests a true culinary experience.  On thing to note, not so many restaurants in Thailand bring you the miang kham when you have dinner. Miang kham is actually the traditional thai snack that people enjoy when they are together. It consists of a bethel leave that you fill with roasted peanuts, coco, lime, shallots and some spicy paste. It is delicious and the perfect snack when you are having a beer or a glass of wine in Thailand but too few restaurants offer this.. I was really happy that Dee Plee has it.  All in all, we would certainly come back and highly recommend it!

Was thoroughly impressed from the time I stepped inside. (Don't let the appearance of the exterior cause you any concern.) The place is small but well-managed. Several tables were full (7:00pm) and our reserved table was ready and waiting. The owner/manager greeted us and promptly seated us. From that point on, service was excellent. The menu (authentic Italian) was full of fantastic choices and made it difficult to pick an entrée. On the server's suggestion, I tried the cauliflower soup appetizer. It was exceptional. My main course, ravioli with lobster meat was a good choice, too.  Overall, the group enjoyed the meal with numerous complements on the food.  If you're in the Manhattan (Hell's Kitchen) area of NYC an want "real" Italian, stop at IL PUNTO for dinner (only open evenings). I don't think you'll be disappointed.
